title: Randomised, Parallel-group, Double-blind Study of Systemic and Ocular Safety and Pharmacokinetics of BI 409306 in Patients With Schizophrenia, Alzheimer's Disease, and Age-comparable Healthy Volunteers
description_brief: Single site, parallel-group, double-blind trial of low or high dose of BI 409306 to evaluate the ocular and systemic safety and pharmacokinetics during 14 day treatment period in patients with schizophrenia, Alzheimer's disease, or age comparable healthy volunteers.

participantFlowModule.preAssignmentDetails: All participants were screened for eligibility to participate in the trial. Participants attended a specialist sites which ensured that they met all strictly implemented inclusion/exclusion criteria. Participants were not to be entered to trial treatment if any one of the specific entry criteria was violated.
participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: The randomised, parallel-group, double-blind study of systemic and ocular safety and pharmacokinetics of BI 409306 in patients with schizophrenia, Alzheimer's disease, and age-comparable healthy volunteers

adverseEventsModule.timeFrame: From the first dose of trial medication until 7 days after last in-take of trial medication, 21 days.
adverseEventsModule.description:
The residual effect period (REP) was defined as 7 days after the last trial medication intake. All adverse events which occurred through the treatment phase and throughout the REP were considered as on treatment.

The treated set (TS) included all participants who were documented to have been administered at least 1 dose of investigational treatment.

drug: BI 409306 (small-molecule PDE9A inhibitor; tested for cognitive improvement in AD and schizophrenia)
explanation_target: Reason: The investigational product is BI 409306, an oral small molecule that selectively inhibits phosphodiesterase 9A (PDE9A). PDE9A inhibition raises intracellular cGMP and is intended to boost NMDA receptor–linked signalling and synaptic plasticity to improve cognition (i.e., symptomatic cognitive enhancement rather than targeting amyloid or tau pathology). citeturn0search0turn0search4

Act: Key extracted details — drug name: BI 409306 (aka osoresnontrine, SUB-166499); drug type/mechanism: potent, selective PDE9A small-molecule inhibitor; clinical intent: studied as a symptomatic cognitive enhancer in Alzheimer’s disease and to improve cognitive dysfunction in schizophrenia; the cited trial is a safety/pharmacokinetic study of low/high dose BI 409306 vs placebo with ocular and systemic safety endpoints over 14 days. citeturn0search2turn0search3turn0search7

Reflect: Classification check — this agent is a small-molecule PDE9A inhibitor tested for symptomatic cognitive effects (phase I/II studies and proof-of-mechanism trials), not a biologic nor a small molecule aimed at core AD pathology (amyloid or tau). Therefore it fits the 'Cognitive enhancer' category. There is no indication in the description that it is intended to modify amyloid/tau or to treat neuropsychiatric symptoms specifically. citeturn0search3turn0search5

Web-search summary (selected results used to support the above): 1) Phase I proof-of-mechanism study showing BI 409306 increases CSF cGMP and crosses into CSF—supports PDE9A mechanism and cognition focus. citeturn0search0; 2) Overview of Phase I trials showing BI 409306 is a selective PDE9A inhibitor with noted ocular AEs at higher exposure. citeturn0search1; 3) Phase II proof-of-concept studies assessed BI 409306 for symptomatic cognitive treatment in prodromal/mild AD. citeturn0search3; 4) Phase IC study in schizophrenia evaluated safety, PK, and cognitive outcomes. citeturn0search5; 5) Chemical/product pages identify BI 409306 (osoresnontrine) and its PDE9A potency/selectivity. citeturn0search2
explanation_agent: Reason: BI 409306 (osoresnontrine) is a selective phosphodiesterase‑9A (PDE9A) inhibitor developed to raise intracellular cGMP and boost NMDA receptor–linked signalling and synaptic plasticity with the goal of improving cognition (i.e., symptomatic cognitive enhancement rather than modifying amyloid or tau). citeturn0search1turn0search3

Act: Key extracted details — drug: BI 409306 (small‑molecule PDE9A inhibitor); mechanism: increases cGMP and promotes synaptic plasticity (proof‑of‑mechanism shows CSF penetration and dose‑dependent CSF cGMP increases); clinical intent: studied as a symptomatic cognitive enhancer (safety/PK and cognitive outcome trials in schizophrenia and AD). Based on these details, assign CADRO category M) Synaptic Plasticity/Neuroprotection. citeturn0search3turn0search2turn0search5

Reflect: The agent targets synaptic signalling/plasticity (an enzyme that modulates intracellular signalling), not core AD pathologies such as amyloid‑beta or tau, nor a multi‑pathway biological target — therefore M is the most specific CADRO match. If the intervention had been aimed at amyloid, tau, inflammation, vasculature, or multiple distinct mechanisms, a different CADRO code would be appropriate. citeturn0search5turn0search4

Supporting web results used: phase I proof‑of‑mechanism showing BI‑409306 increases CSF cGMP and crosses into CSF (BI‑409306 pharmacokinetics/pharmacodynamics). citeturn0search3; PubMed Phase IC study in schizophrenia reporting safety, PK, and cognitive outcomes. citeturn0search2; Phase II cognitive trials in schizophrenia/AD (no significant cognitive benefit in larger phase II study referenced). citeturn0search5; product/chemistry pages and vendor summaries describing BI‑409306 (osoresnontrine) as a potent, selective PDE9A inhibitor. citeturn0search1turn0search0
